\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
a) According to EUT, A preferred to B translates in 
\begin_inset Formula $u(10)\geq\frac{1}{2}u(24)+\frac{1}{2}u(0).$
\end_inset

 Multiplying by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

 both sides and adding 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}u(0)$
\end_inset

 on both sides, one finds 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2}{3}u(10)+\frac{1}{3}u(0)\geq\frac{1}{3}u(24)+\frac{2}{3}u(0),$
\end_inset

 which translates into C preferred to D.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, the combination A preferred to B and D preferred to C is not
 consistent with EUT.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
b) For A preferred to B and D preferred to C to be consistent with prospect
 theory we must have both:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\pi(1)u(10) & \geq\pi(\frac{1}{2})u(24)+\pi(\frac{1}{2})u(0)\\
 & \text{and}\\
\pi(\frac{2}{3})u(10)+\pi(\frac{1}{3})u(0) & \leq\pi(\frac{1}{3})u(24)+\pi(\frac{2}{3})u(0)\end{align}

\end_inset

 Normalizing 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=0$
\end_inset

 (this is allowed as the utility function is unique up to a linear transformatio
n) this can be rewritten into the following condition:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{\pi(1)}{\pi(\frac{1}{2})}\geq\frac{u(24)}{u(10)}\geq\frac{\pi(\frac{2}{3})}{\pi(\frac{1}{3})}\end{equation}

\end_inset

I will show that this can occur under some specification of the function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(.).$
\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(.)$
\end_inset

 is a continuously increasing function, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\frac{1}{3})=\frac{1}{3},$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)>x$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x<\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)<x$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x>\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 (this fits common assumption about the shape of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(.)$
\end_inset

 function and corresponds to some empirical findings), and suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=x$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (risk neutral agent).
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(1)=1.$
\end_inset

 The condition above can then be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\pi(\frac{1}{2})}\geq\frac{24}{10}\geq3\pi(\frac{2}{3})\end{equation}

\end_inset

 so I must have and This is consistent with prospect theory, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\frac{2}{3})\leq\frac{2.4}{3}$
\end_inset

 from the fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(x)<x$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x>\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi(\frac{1}{2})\leq\frac{10}{24}$
\end_inset

, while more stringent than what we assumed, does not contradict PT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
c) Under regret theory, A preferred to B translates in
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}r(10,0)+\frac{1}{2}r(10,24)\geq0\end{equation}

\end_inset

 while D preferred to C translates in 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\frac{1}{3}r(24,0)+\frac{2}{3}r(0,10)\geq0\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In regret theory, one will generally expect 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)>r(x,z)+r(z,y)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in]y,x[$
\end_inset

 (rejoice increases more than proportionally in the size of the difference
 between bad and good outcome).
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $r(24,0)>r(24,10)+r(10,0)$
\end_inset

 (condition A).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One will also expect that 
\begin_inset Formula $r(x,y)=-r(y,x)$
\end_inset

 (symmetry between rejoice and regret) and allows one to rewrite the two
 equations as
\begin_inset Formula \[
r(10,0)\geq r(24,10)\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \[
r(24,0)\geq2r(10,0)\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I can accept that the first equation is verified (the feeling of rejoicing
 when getting 24 rather than 10 may be less than from getting 10 rather
 than nothing).
 If that first equation is verified, the second equation is more stringent
 than condition A.
 However, while more stringent than usual assumptions of RT, the second
 equation does not contradict it in any way.
 Therefore, such preferences are consistent with regret theory.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
