\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
a) The utility of rejecting the lottery is 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln(w)$
\end_inset

 (the individual is left with the same wealth as before), while if the individua
l plays the lottery, then she either loses 
\begin_inset Formula $\pounds10$
\end_inset

, in which case wealth is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $w-10,$
\end_inset

 or she gains 
\begin_inset Formula $\pounds10,$
\end_inset

 in which case her wealth is 
\begin_inset Formula $w+11.$
\end_inset

 The expected utility of playing the lottery is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\ln(w-10)+\frac{1}{2}\ln(w+11),$
\end_inset

 and rejecting the lottery translates by EUT in 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}\ln(w-10)+\frac{1}{2}\ln(w+11)\leq\ln(w).$
\end_inset

 A straightforward transformation obtains the result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
b) Transforming the inequality in 
\begin_inset Formula $a),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\ln(w-10)+\ln(w+11) & \leq2\ln(w)\\
(w-10)(w+11) & \leq w^{2}\\
w & \leq110\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
c) The individual accepts subject to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\ln(109-100)+\ln(109+Y) & \geq2\ln(109)\\
Y & \geq\frac{109^{2}}{9}-109\\
Y & \geq1211.111...\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
d) The individual accepts subject to 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{align}
\ln(200-100)+\ln(200+Z) & \geq2\ln(200)\\
Z & \geq\frac{200^{2}}{100}-200\\
Z & \geq200\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout List
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
e) Whether an individual accepts or rejects a lottery depends on his wealth
 as much as on the shape of his utility function.
 Losses that are big with respect to one's wealth require high compensation.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $c),$
\end_inset

 the individual requests a very high 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 to compensate for the risk to lose 
\begin_inset Formula $100.$
\end_inset

 The expected value of the lottery is then required to be at least 
\begin_inset Formula $\pounds555.$
\end_inset

 It would seem irrational to reject it, but then, one must put oneself in
 the situation where one risks to lose 92% of one wealth, vs.
 the chance to multiply it by 11.
 Would you necessarily accept it?
\end_layout

